# Evaluating Neural Architecture Search Methods

## Abstract

We compare three neural architecture search (NAS) methods on standard benchmarks. Our experiments show that weight-sharing approaches achieve competitive accuracy with significantly reduced search cost.

## Experimental Setup

All experiments were conducted on a cluster with 8 NVIDIA A100 GPUs. We used the following hyperparameters:

| Parameter | Value |
| --- | ---: |
| Learning rate | 0.025 |
| Batch size | 256 |
| Weight decay | 0.0003 |
| Epochs | 600 |
| Optimizer | SGD with momentum |

Table: Training hyperparameters {#hyperparams}

## Results

### CIFAR-10

![CIFAR-10 accuracy comparison](figures/cifar10-accuracy.png "Accuracy curves on CIFAR-10")

| Method | Params (M) | Accuracy (%) | GPU Hours |
| --- | ---: | ---: | ---: |
| DARTS | 3.3 | 97.24 | 1.5 |
| ENAS | 4.6 | 97.11 | 0.5 |
| NASNet | 3.3 | 97.35 | 48000 |
| Random Search | 3.2 | 97.05 | 4.0 |

Table: CIFAR-10 benchmark results {#cifar10-results}

### ImageNet

![ImageNet top-1 accuracy](figures/imagenet-top1.png "Top-1 accuracy on ImageNet validation set")

The weight-sharing method achieves **76.2%** top-1 accuracy while requiring only *0.5 GPU days* for the search phase.

## Analysis

N> The search cost of NASNet (48000 GPU hours) makes it impractical for most research labs.

W> Accuracy numbers should be interpreted carefully. Small differences (less than 0.3%) may not be statistically significant.

## Conclusion

Weight-sharing NAS methods offer the best trade-off between search efficiency and final accuracy. We recommend DARTS as the default choice for architecture search on image classification tasks.

[^darts]: Liu, H. et al. (2019). DARTS: Differentiable Architecture Search.
